subSection.paragraph:
Ceratopogonids are one of the most important and diverse groups within the nematocerous Diptera . The family Ceratopogonidae is well known for its medico-veterinary importance (
Lee et al . 1963
; Yeh & Chuang 1996 ;
Chen et al . 2005
). Worldwide, there are 6206 extant species placed in three subfamilies belonging to 112 genera ( Borkent & Dominiak 2020 ). The genus
Forcipomyia Meigen, 1818
is the second largest speciose group within the family Ceratopogonidae , showing an astonishing diversity with 1142 species worldwide distributed into 36 different subgenera ( Borkent & Dominiak 2020 ). Till date in India , a total of 83 species of Forcipomya are known (
Saha et al . 2009
; Pal & Hazra 2022 ;
Pal et al . 2023
;
Pal et al . 2024 a
, b).

Like most of the other ceratopogonids, 

Forcipomyia

has also shown a wide range of feeding diversity such as hematophagous, hemolymphophagous, pollinophagous and necterophagous (
Szadziewski 2016
). Numerous species belonging to this genus have also been documented as ectoparasites of insects across multiple orders (
Wirth 1956
; 
Tokunaga & Murachi 1959
).

subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis.
Only species of 

Forcipomyia
(
Lepidohelea
)

from the 
Oriental
realm is separated by the large swollen gonostylus base (
Fig. 2I
); tarsomere I of hind leg abruptly swollen at the middle; caudomedian excavation ‘U” shaped (
Fig. 2J
); submedian process of parameres short with blunt end (
Fig. 2F
); basal arms of aedeagus long, roughly triangular (
Fig. 2G
); two large spermathecae without any neck and punctation, oval shaped (
Fig. 2P
).

subSection.paragraph:
Head
. Dark brown; eyes contiguous, bare. Small scales and setae present on vertex. Antennae with pale brown flagellomeres (
Fig. 2A
); flagellomeres I and X–XIII elongated; II–IX vasiform; all flagellomeres having sensilla chaetica, terminal four flagellomeres (X–XIII) bearing sensilla basiconica, sensilla trichodea; sensilla chaetica of II–XII with a combination of black and yellow color. Proportion of length of flagellomeres (I–XIII): 25–31 (28.3): 18–20 (19.3): 18–19 (18.3): 18–19 (18.3): 16–18 (17.3): 17–18 (17.6): 18–19 (18.3): 18–20 (19.5): 19–22 (20.3): 60–62 (61): 33–35 (34): 20–24 (22.33): 30–32 (31); AR:1.03–1.14 (1.07). Maxillary palp brown; proportion of length of palpomeres (I–V): 10–13 (11.3): 11–13 (12): 24–26 (24.6): 10–12 (11): 12–15 (13); 
PR
: 2.18–2.66 (2.48); palpomere III cylindrical, distal end tapered, a small rounded sensory pit located subapically bearing 6–7 protruded capitate sensilla (
Fig. 2B
). Mandible and maxilla without any teeth.

